{"$message_type":"diagnostic","message":"the trait bound `byteorder::F32<O>: IntoBytes` is not satisfied","code":{"code":"E0277","explanation":"You tried to use a type which doesn't implement some trait in a place which\nexpected that trait.\n\nErroneous code example:\n\n```compile_fail,E0277\n// here we declare the Foo trait with a bar method\ntrait Foo {\n    fn bar(&self);\n}\n\n// we now declare a function which takes an object implementing the Foo trait\nfn some_func<T: Foo>(foo: T) {\n    foo.bar();\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    // we now call the method with the i32 type, which doesn't implement\n    // the Foo trait\n    some_func(5i32); // error: the trait bound `i32 : Foo` is not satisfied\n}\n```\n\nIn order to fix this error, verify that the type you're using does implement\nthe trait. Example:\n\n```\ntrait Foo {\n    fn bar(&self);\n}\n\n// we implement the trait on the i32 type\nimpl Foo for i32 {\n    fn bar(&self) {}\n}\n\nfn some_func<T: Foo>(foo: T) {\n    foo.bar(); // we can now use this method since i32 implements the\n               // Foo trait\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    some_func(5i32); // ok!\n}\n```\n\nOr in a generic context, an erroneous code example would look like:\n\n```compile_fail,E0277\nfn some_func<T>(foo: T) {\n    println!(\"{:?}\", foo); // error: the trait `core::fmt::Debug` is not\n                           //        implemented for the type `T`\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    // We now call the method with the i32 type,\n    // which *does* implement the Debug trait.\n    some_func(5i32);\n}\n```\n\nNote that the error here is in the definition of the generic function. Although\nwe only call it with a parameter that does implement `Debug`, the compiler\nstill rejects the function. It must work with all possible input types. In\norder to make this example compile, we need to restrict the generic type we're\naccepting:\n\n```\nuse std::fmt;\n\n// Restrict the input type to types that implement Debug.\nfn some_func<T: fmt::Debug>(foo: T) {\n    println!(\"{:?}\", foo);\n}\n\nfn main() {\n    // Calling the method is still fine, as i32 implements Debug.\n    some_func(5i32);\n\n    // This would fail to compile now:\n    // struct WithoutDebug;\n    // some_func(WithoutDebug);\n}\n```\n\nRust only looks at the signature of the called function, as such it must\nalready specify all requirements that will be used for every type parameter.\n"},"level":"error","spans":[{"file_name":"C:\\Users\\25919\\.cargo\\registry\\src\\index.crates.io-1949cf8c6b5b557f\\zerocopy-0.8.40\\src\\byteorder.rs","byte_start":19564,"byte_end":19572,"line_start":504,"line_end":504,"column_start":48,"column_end":56,"is_primary":true,"text":[{"text":"            impl_or_verify!(O => IntoBytes for $name<O>);","highlight_start":48,"highlight_end":56}],"label":"unsatisfied trait bound","suggested_replacement":null,"suggestion_applicability":null,"expansion":{"span":{"file_name":"C:\\Users\\25919\\.cargo\\registry\\src\\index.crates.io-1949cf8c6b5b557f\\zerocopy-0.8.40\\src\\byteorder.rs","byte_start":30267,"byte_end":30535,"line_start":905,"line_end":921,"column_start":1,"column_end":2,"is_primary":false,"text":[{"text":"define_type!(","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":14},{"text":"    An,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":8},{"text":"    \"A 32-bit floating point number\",","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":38},{"text":"    F32,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":9},{"text":"    f32,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":9},{"text":"    32,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":8},{"text":"    4,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":7},{"text":"    f32_ext::from_be_bytes,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":28},{"text":"    f32_ext::to_be_bytes,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":26},{"text":"    f32_ext::from_le_bytes,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":28},{"text":"    f32_ext::to_le_bytes,","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":26},{"text":"    \"floating point number\",","highlight_start":1,"highlight_end":29},{"text":"    [f